## 1. Introduction: The Multi-Scale xMHD Challenge

The pursuit of predictive magnetic confinement fusion requires resolving plasma dynamics spanning twelve orders of magnitude in time: from rapid electron cyclotron motion ($\sim 10^{-11}$ s) to macroscopic resistive wall modes ($\sim 10^1$ s) [1]. The extended MHD equations couple these fast waves with highly anisotropic heat transport ($\chi_\parallel / \chi_\perp \sim 10^9$) and localized tearing mode instabilities.

Standard numerical integration architectures encounter three fundamental barriers:

1. **The Stiffness Barrier:** Explicit integrators are constrained by nanosecond Alfvén Courant–Friedrichs–Lewy (CFL) conditions, while fully implicit solvers yield severely ill-conditioned Jacobians.
2. **The Dimensionality Barrier:** Resolving dissipative tearing layers requires $\mathcal{O}(10^8 - 10^{10})$ degrees of freedom, rendering direct or dense Jacobian inversions computationally intractable.
3. **The Anisotropy Barrier:** Extreme parallel-to-perpendicular transport ratios destroy the convergence of standard Cartesian algebraic multigrid (AMG) preconditioners [2].

In this work, we transition from monolithic architectures to `rusty-SUNDIALS`—a memory-safe, concurrent Rust implementation of the SUNDIALS suite [3]. We mitigate the aforementioned barriers utilizing physics-constrained machine learning routing, mixed-precision preconditioners, and structure-preserving reduced-order manifolds.

