## 4. Field-Aligned Graph Neural Preconditioning (FLAGNO)

### 4.1 Topology-Aware Operator Learning

Standard finite-difference preconditioners fail because magnetic diffusion along the field line $\mathbf{B}$ outpaces cross-field transport by orders of magnitude. We formulate the spatial domain as a dynamic graph $\mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{E})$ where edges $\mathcal{E}$ are weighted along the magnetic field topology:

$$ \mathcal{E}_{\text{aligned}} = \left\{ (i,j) : \left| \left\langle \frac{\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{x}_i}{\|\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{x}_i\|}, \hat{\mathbf{b}}_i \right\rangle \right| > \cos\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) \right\} $$

A Graph Neural Operator (GNO) [5] predicts the preconditioning action $\mathbf{M}^{-1}\mathbf{v}$ using Tensor Cores in mixed-precision FP8.

### 4.2 Application to Toroidal Proxy Geometry

Evaluated on a coarse-grained ITER topological proxy ($32 \times 32 \times 32$ grid; 32,768 cells; $B_0 = 6.37$ T):

* **Connectivity:** The field-aligned graph generated 492,096 edges, accurately mapping the helical pitch of the field, compared to 196,608 edges in a standard 6-point Cartesian stencil.
* **FGMRES Iterations:** Using FLAGNO as a right-preconditioner reduced required Krylov iterations from 99 (block-Jacobi) to 5.

Because Flexible GMRES (FGMRES) evaluates the outer residual in exact FP64, any FP8 quantization error in the preconditioner only affects the convergence rate, preserving the strict FP64 physical accuracy of the converged state.

