## 7. Conclusion

The transition toward high-speed, predictive control in fusion simulation requires discarding strictly monolithic solvers in favor of topology-aware, mixed-precision, and structure-preserving methodologies. This work demonstrates that spectral IMEX splitting, divergence-free latent manifolds, field-aligned graph preconditioners, and asynchronous sensitivities can systematically mitigate the stiffness, dimensionality, and anisotropy bottlenecks of xMHD. While currently validated on coarse-grained proxy geometries, the mathematically bounded subroutines implemented in `rusty-SUNDIALS` outline a robust, scalable architecture for next-generation macroscopic plasma control surrogates.

